		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Culture war</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p>The <b>culture war</b> (or <b>culture wars</b>) in <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">American</a> usage is a metaphor used to claim that political conflict is based on sets of conflicting cultural values. The term frequently implies a conflict between those values considered traditional or <a href="/wiki/Conservativism_in_the_United_States" title="Conservativism in the United States" class="mw-redirect">conservative</a> and those considered <a href="/wiki/Progressivism_in_the_United_States" title="Progressivism in the United States">progressive</a> or <a href="/wiki/Modern_liberalism_in_the_United_States" title="Modern liberalism in the United States">liberal</a>. The "culture war" is sometimes traced to the 1960s and has taken various forms since then.</p>
